\renewcommand{\abstractname}{Abstract}
\begin{abstract}
Social security, from its origins to the present day, was created as a measure to promote equity among individuals in a society, with the goal of providing dignified living conditions. The issue that all social security systems around the world currently face is related to population aging and its financial impact on pension fund reserves. For this reason, actions must be taken to ensure the short-, medium-, and long-term sustainability of the funds managed by social security institutions, especially those related to retirement pensions.

Ecuador is no exception to this global crisis, and, compounded by the deterioration of its local economy, its pension fund is being forced to divest its reserves at an alarming rate to ensure the payment of obligations to current pensioners. This has led to liquidity and sustainability problems for the fund in the short term.

In this context, the first part of this Master's Thesis focuses on classifying the contributions made by current pensioners throughout their working lives. To carry out this analysis, various clustering algorithms, such as hierarchical clustering, K-Means, and DBSCAN, will be implemented. Through these methods, the contributions will be organized into groups, allowing for the identification of patterns and the detection of which of these contributions are fraudulent.

The second part of this work focuses on conducting an adequate KDD process, including feature selection through dimensionality reduction techniques and the use of unsupervised methods. Subsequently, various supervised learning techniques will be implemented, including KNN, decision trees, ensemble methods, XGBoost, and neural networks, all of which are oriented towards classification tasks. With the application of these methodologies, several predictive models will be developed, and the model that offers the most optimal results will be selected. This selection will not only be based on the model's ability to classify accurately but also on its capacity to detect outliers in the data and avoid overfitting, ensuring that the chosen model maintains an appropriate balance between precision and generalization to new data. Additionally, the execution time of each model and the computational cost of its implementation will be considered, ensuring that the chosen solution is both efficient and effective in predicting the salary behavior of current affiliates. Furthermore, an analysis will be conducted to estimate the potential savings that the Ecuadorian pension system could achieve if fraudulent contributions were excluded.

The training process for the models will include cross-validation techniques to assess performance and hyperparameter optimization to improve the accuracy and effectiveness of the predictions obtained.

\vspace{0.5cm}

\keywords{aprendizaje no supervisado, KNN, conjunto de modelos, XGBoost, redes neuronales, hiperparámetros}
\end{abstract}

